pan></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;From the speaker: &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll be there momentarily.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And as if she had been waiting right outside the door, she enters the room with a deck of Uno cards which she places down on the table in the center of the tea room. &ldquo;Will that be all?&rdquo; she asks, already beginning to turn around.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Actually,&rdquo; Marc says, &ldquo;Uno is awfully boring with only two people. Since Aidan and Marissa are off on their antidote hunt, we could really use another player.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I see,&rdquo; April says, nodding. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s a shame. Perhaps one of the Figments would like to play with you.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; Arlene cuts in, &ldquo;we were really hoping that, maybe, you would join us?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Afraid not.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Oh, well, would you mind bringing us some biscuits to go with this tea?&rdquo; Arlene asks quickly, catching April before she leaves the room. April stops in the doorway, glances at the tables still full of hot food, and sighs.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Very well, I will make you some </span><span class="c1 c7">fresh</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;biscuits.&rdquo; She picks up the tray of already made biscuits from one of the tables and exits the grand hall.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Biscuits? Really?&rdquo; Marc says with a laugh.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;It was the best I could think of to keep her around,&rdquo; Arlene says with an awkward smile.</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c1">#</span></p><p class="c3 c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the kitchen, April shakes her head and takes a bite out of one of the uneaten biscuits. She pulls out some premade biscuit dough from the massive double fridge and begins shaping it into small lumps. Around her, those cookie-cutter, blank-faced Figments run back and forth across the kitchen&mdash;some stuffing trays into the oven or pulling finished meals out, others garnishing colorful dishes with various spices and edible decorations. She tosses one dough ball onto the plate and begins shaping another one.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Hi there!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">She staggers back, one hand jumping to her heart and breath coming fast as she gawks at an overenthusiastic Arlene. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;How&rsquo;s the food going?&rdquo; Arlene continues. &ldquo;I thought I&rsquo;d visit the kitchen and help you out! </span><span class="c1">Pass me some dough, yo.</span><span class="c1">&rdquo; She laughs. &ldquo;Oh my, that sounded far sillier than even I expected.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">April rolls her eyes, tosses the lump of dough to Arlene, and walks out of the kitchen.</span></p><p class="c0 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c1">#</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marc leans against the wall in the hallway outside the kitchen. &ldquo;I told Arly to leave you be while you were working,&rdquo; he says as April walks out into the hall, &ldquo;but she&rsquo;s pretty stubborn someti&mdash; Hey, wait! Where are you going?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Without responding, April walks past him and turns into the center hallway. Arlene runs out of the kitchen, </span><span class="c1">raw dough still on her hands</span><span class="c1">. She wipes this carelessly on her dress before placing her out turned wrists on her hips and staring down the hall. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Marc, you let her go!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;She was practically running away after whatever you did in the kitchen.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Arlene puffs out her cheeks. &ldquo;This isn&rsquo;t working.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c1"># &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Back in the tea room, Marc and Arlene sip at their quickly cooling tea. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what to do to convince her to join in,&rdquo; Arlene complains. &ldquo;I just know she&rsquo;d have fun if she did, but she&rsquo;s being so stubborn.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;You&rsquo;re pretty stubborn yourself, Arly. You could just let it go, you know.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;No way. I&rsquo;ve made up my mind, and she&rsquo;s joining this party.&rdquo; She crosses her arms matter-of-factly. &ldquo;And I&rsquo;m not stubborn; I&rsquo;m determined.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc laughs. &ldquo;Whatever you say, </span><span class="c1">lil miss rich and stubborn&mdash;</span><span class="c1">&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Hey!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;&mdash;but I think I&rsquo;ll have a chat with April myself. I don&rsquo;t know if I&rsquo;ll be able to convince her to join us, but I think you&rsquo;re right; it would be good for her to make some friends.&rdquo; With that, he stands up from his seat, gulps down the rest of his tea, and leaves the grand hall. &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c3 c10 c5"><a name="h.9r4jtk4ku3qb"></a><span class="c6">4.5 Halloween Special</span></h3><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c1">(</span><span class="c1 c8"><a class="c13" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=http://midnightmurderparty.com/interactive/HalloweenSpecial2015&amp;sa=D&amp;usg=AFQjCNH_fZTEfXli1OdYx1-kpMETdJU8qw">Click here to go trick or treating with Arlene!</a></span><span class="c1">)</span></p><p class="c3 c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c3 c10 c5"><a name="h.awdud4erls7r"></a><span class="c6">5</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Back in the sitting room, Marissa and Aidan sit on one of the pretty, white sofas staring intently down at Arlene&rsquo;s riddle, which is laid out on the table in front of them. Marissa leans back and tugs at her hair with a frustrated growl.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;This makes, like, no sense. How are we even suppose to figure this out? Ugh, Arlene did this on purpose. She knows I&rsquo;m bad at riddles.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span class="c1">Aidan lifts a tentative finger and pokes Marissa on the cheek. &ldquo;Boop.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;What are you doing!?&rdquo; Marissa yells as Aidan dives under a pillow, giggling.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Nothing,&rdquo; he says in the voice of a kid who clearly knows he&rsquo;s doing </span><span class="c1 c7">something</span><span class="c1">. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Well, quit it ya little creep,&rdquo; Marissa retorts as she looks back at the riddle. &ldquo;And help me figure this out.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Okay,&rdquo; Aidan says, wriggling out from under the pillow, his hair in messy, little tufts and his face glowing red. He turns his attention to the paper on the table.</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">I am the house of many worlds,</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">now mark my words in silence:</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">A two-faced man and lightning&#39;s mark.</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">Between the faces you will find it.</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Hey, look at the last line,&rdquo; Marissa says, pointing. &ldquo;&lsquo;Between the faces you will find it.&rsquo; That&rsquo;s where the flask is, right?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I think so.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;So it&rsquo;s gotta be in someone&rsquo;s head. Oh! Maybe we have to blow up Marc&rsquo;s head again!&rdquo; She grins and pulls Marc&rsquo;s eye out of her pocket, flicks it into the air, and snatches it back. Then she raises her hands to her ears, her fingers pressed together in little pincers, one of them dangling the eyeball below her ear. &ldquo;Forget the ring, I&rsquo;m making earrings!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;But&hellip; it says &lsquo;two-faced man&rsquo;. That doesn&rsquo;t sound like Marc.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Oh, we&rsquo;re looking for a man? You&rsquo;re right, that doesn&rsquo;t sound like Marc.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Hey! He&rsquo;s a&mdash;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Yeah, yeah. Okay, so we need to find a two-faced man and split his head open.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Umm&hellip; I&rsquo;m not so sure about that.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Oh, yeah? So what&rsquo;s the little stalker boy think then?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan winces as she says this and diverts his eyes to the floor.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Well, c&rsquo;mon, what is it already,&rdquo; she presses, a note of irritation digging into her voice. &ldquo;Maybe you forgot, but we&rsquo;re on a time limit here.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;W-well, what if it&rsquo;s not really a &lsquo;man&rsquo; at all?&rdquo; Aidan finally manages, still not looking up. &ldquo;Like, what if it&rsquo;s something else with faces?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marissa smirks. &ldquo;Like what?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Umm&hellip; well, maybe a dollar bill?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;It wouldn&rsquo;t be in between a dollar bill, stupid. And there&rsquo;s only one face on those anyway.&rdquo; She pauses and puckers her lips to one side, staring at the last lines of the riddle. &ldquo;What about a mirror? Like, you look into a mirror and there&rsquo;s your face and your face reflected in the mirror. So it&rsquo;s between you and... the mirror?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan scrunches his face. &ldquo;But there are probably lots of mirrors in this house, right?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marissa frowns. &ldquo;Yeah, good point. What else has faces, though?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Umm&hellip; what about a clock?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Like the one in the grand hall!&rdquo; Marissa exclaims. Without waiting, she vaults over the back of the sofa and darts towards the grand hall. Aidan glances at the riddle one more time before following her under the arch.</span></p><p class="c0 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c3 c5 c10"><a name="h.wzrsv3mk5o1z"></a><span class="c6">6</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc strolls down the large hallway, glancing at various busts that rest atop stands in the alcoves as he goes. Most of them look like Arlene. He turns down the hall that extends into the center of the mansion without bothering to look at the floor below him. His foot barely skims over the top of the little silver wire that is stretched across the ground, and, </span><span class="c1">none the wiser, </span><span class="c1">he continues past the door to the theater and turns right into yet another hall which he follows to the end. He stops at a small door with a plaque that reads &ldquo;Servants&rsquo; Quarters&rdquo; and </span><span class="c1">raps</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;on the door with his knuckles. After a moment of silence, the door swings back to reveal April.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She stands half a head shorter than Marc and eyes him warily, but not impolitely, with her cool, grey eyes. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Is there something you&rsquo;d like?&rdquo; she asks in her mild tone. &ldquo;You didn&rsquo;t have to come over here yourself, you know. You could have just used the buzzer.&rdquo; She gestures at a small box on the wall of the servants&rsquo; room.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Well, I figured I&rsquo;d save you the trouble,&rdquo; Marc says, peering into the room as if he&rsquo;d never seen it before. His eyes catch on a game of Solitaire sprawled out on a table. &ldquo;You like card games?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She glances back at her game. &ldquo;I guess.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;That&rsquo;s Solitaire, right? My brother and I used to play that together when we were little.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Together?&rdquo; she says, eyebrows raised.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc laughs. &ldquo;Yeah, I guess playing something that&rsquo;s practically named &lsquo;solitary&rsquo; with another person kinda defeats the purpose.&rdquo; He pauses, looking thoughtfully at the cards. &ldquo;But we had fun. Had our own set of rules and everything.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;That&rsquo;s weird.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Not weird. House rules. Hey, how &lsquo;bout I show you how we used to play?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I think I&rsquo;d rather just finish my own game,&rdquo; she says, half closing the the door before Marc can speak again.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Woah, wait a sec,&rdquo; Marc exclaims, pulling his hand away from the closing door. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Yes?&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Would you mind if I came in? I never did learn to play with the real rules.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She looks at him doubtfully for a moment and then sighs. &ldquo;Fine. But leave the door open.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They move to the couch in the servants&rsquo; room. On one side of the room, there are big windows that, during just the right time of day, may cast golden afternoon light across the creamy white carpet that matches the couches. On the other is a folded wooden screen behind which servants could change for work. Though, from the barren look of that corner, Figments needn&rsquo;t use changing rooms too often.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span class="c1">April studies the cards</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;on the table, </span><span class="c1">plucks out a Four of Hearts and places it down on a Five of Clubs</span><span class="c1">. &ldquo;You have to alternate the colors,&rdquo; she says, not looking up at Marc. &ldquo;You want to get a full stack, King all the way down to Two, if possible.&rdquo;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;What happens when you finish the stack?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Nothing, it just stays there. The stacks are just intermediary. You really want to build the Foundations.&rdquo; She points at the top right of the game board where three Aces are lined up, some with cards on top of them.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Doesn&rsquo;t sound too hard.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She looks up at him with an expression that seems to say &ldquo;oh yeah?&rdquo; and instead says, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s harder than it looks. What would your next move be?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc stares at the available cards for a moment before saying, &ldquo;Just move that Queen onto that King.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;You can&rsquo;t. Wrong color.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Oh, right. Umm&hellip; in that case&hellip;&rdquo; He goes back to perusing the cards, his eyes darting from one card to the bottom of the next stack followed by a subtle head-shake and more studying. &ldquo;What do you do if you get stuck?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc catches a little smirk on April&rsquo;s face, and as soon as he sees, it flashes away. &ldquo;In that case, you have to move more cards into the Waste&mdash;to see if there are any more moves you can make.&rdquo; She pulls more cards from the deck and frowns.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t see any useful cards,&rdquo; Marc says.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I know.&rdquo; She cycles the deck again. Still nothing. Again a few more times before she leans back and sighs.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;What is it,&rdquo; Marc asks.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;A losing hand. Not as easy as it looks, huh?&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Seriously? We lost?&rdquo;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Seriously.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0">