at was funny.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marc, whose face is now a little flushed, waves it off. &ldquo;Yeah, yeah. Oh, I&rsquo;ve got an idea for a bet. Do you have any poker chips?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">April quietly gets up and walks to the closet in the back of the room where she rummages around for a minute before pulling out a poker set.</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t really know how poker chips work,&rdquo; Marc says, &ldquo;but ten chips each should be fine. Let&rsquo;s just say color doesn&rsquo;t matter.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">She nods and deals them both ten chips.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;So how about this,&rdquo; Marc continues. &ldquo;Whoever ends up with all the chips wins. If I win, you join the party with the rest of us. And if you&mdash;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;No thank you.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marc falls silent, his mouth hanging where his last word had ended.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to join the party. I&rsquo;ve said it before, and I would appreciate it if you and Arlene would stop asking.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">The room stays quiet, save for the sound of their breathing, as Marc searches for something to say. Finally, he settles on: &ldquo;Okay, I get it. Then let&rsquo;s try this instead. If </span><span class="c1 c7">you</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;win, we&rsquo;ll all leave you alone. We won&rsquo;t ask you to join in again if you don&rsquo;t want to. But if </span><span class="c1 c7">I</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;win, you join only for the next story. You don&rsquo;t have to speak to us, you don&rsquo;t have to participate in the actual game, and you can leave whenever you like, including during the story if you are really having a terrible time. Does that sound fair?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Again the room falls quiet as April looks from Marc to the card game laid out on the table. She furrows her brow as she thinks, and Marc leans back, patiently awaiting her response. Then, she puts one finger on a poker piece, nudges it into the center of the table and says, &ldquo;Ante up.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c3 c10 c5"><a name="h.1xx21ss2ujxc"></a><span class="c6">7</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;C&rsquo;mon, kid. Help me push this stupid clock off the wall,&rdquo; Marissa says, heaving all her weight into the grandfather clock. Aidan pushes harder, but it doesn&rsquo;t budge.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Oh my, what on Earth are you two up to?&rdquo; Arlene asks, gliding across the grand hall to where Aidan and Marissa stand with beads of sweat forming along their brows.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Trying&hellip; to find&hellip; the antidote,&rdquo; Marissa grunts between shoves.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Ahh, yes, and I suppose you found my clue?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; Aidan responds, easing off the clock. &ldquo;We think that, maybe, the clock has two faces&mdash;one on the front and one on the back, only the back one&rsquo;s hidden. Two faces, like in the riddle.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Hey, don&rsquo;t stop pushing!&rdquo; Marissa grumbles.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Ah! Sorry!&rdquo; Aidan says, leaning into the clock again.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Arlene laughs. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t worry about her, Aidan. She&rsquo;s grouchy with everybody.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Nuh-uh! Only with people who </span><span class="c18">cre</span><span class="c12">ep</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span><span class="c12">m</span><span class="c16">e</span><span class="c9">&nbsp;o-</span><span class="c1">...&rdquo; Marissa&rsquo;s sentence trails off abruptly, and she sways on her feet. One hand latches onto the wall for support, and the other grabs her head. </span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;What&rsquo;s wrong?&rdquo; Aidan asks with innocent urgency. Arlene laughs.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;It looks like it&rsquo;s starting to kick in,&rdquo; she says, casting them a devilish smile. &ldquo;Better figure out that riddle quickly.&rdquo; She makes for the archway.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Wait!&rdquo; Aidan calls. &ldquo;Where are you going?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Just going to catch up on some reading while I wait for your brother to return. He sure is taking his time. I even went tricking or treating while I was waiting!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Oh, okay,&rdquo; Aidan says, looking a little puzzled.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;By the way,&rdquo; Arlene adds as she heads for the arch, &ldquo;that clock only has one face.&rdquo; She leaves the room.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan peeks around the clock at Marissa, who has regained her balance and is now leaning against the clock with her forehead pressed into her palm and her hair falling down around her face in auburn streaks. &ldquo;Hey, uh, are you alright?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Yeah, yeah,&rdquo; she growls, straightening up and trying to blink the bleariness out of her eyes. &ldquo;Relax, I just got kinda dizzy. She said it&rsquo;s not this clock, right? Maybe there&rsquo;s another clock around here somewhere.&rdquo; &nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I guess&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Got a problem, kid?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve just been thinking...&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;That&rsquo;s dangerous.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;About the riddle. We kinda skipped over the first couple lines.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;So?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Could we, maybe, go back to it?&rdquo; He looks at Marissa hopefully and then rushes to add, &ldquo;You know, only if you want to&hellip;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Fine, whatever, not that the stupid riddle&rsquo;s gonna do us any good.&rdquo; She closes her eyes and massages her temple with the heel of her palm. When she opens them again, </span><span class="c1">that piercing, green sharpness </span><span class="c1">has returned to her glare. &ldquo;What are you waiting for? Hurry it up!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">They leave the grand hall and head back to the sitting room where they read over the riddle again. Aidan&rsquo;s eyes skim over the words a couple times. On the third pass, they light up so that the timidness in his face nearly vanishes completely, replaced by excitement and realization. He snatches up the paper and folds it in three places so that the creases separate certain lines of the riddle.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;The hell you doing?&rdquo; Marissa says. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m trying to read that, you know.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan flinches at her outburst, but doesn&rsquo;t pause. &ldquo;Look at the punctuation,&rdquo; he says, spreading the paper on the table before them again. The riddle now reads:</span></p><p class="c0 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">I am the house of many worlds,</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">now mark my words in silence:</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; </span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">A two-faced man and lightning&#39;s mark.</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;</span></p><p class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">Between the faces you will find it.</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t get it,&rdquo; Marissa says, sounding both bored and annoyed, but moreso the latter. &ldquo;You folded the paper. So what?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;The punctuation, doesn&rsquo;t it seem to separate different thoughts?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marissa stares at the page again, frowning. &ldquo;I guess,&rdquo; she finally says, not sounding at all convinced. &ldquo;So, you wanna take it from the beginning or something?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Uh-huh.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marissa shrugs resignedly. &ldquo;Alright, fine. &lsquo;I am the house of many worlds&rsquo;,&rdquo; she reads, &ldquo;whatever </span><span class="c1 c7">that</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;means.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan doesn&rsquo;t respond right away. He stares at the first line for a moment before speaking. &ldquo;I think it&rsquo;s talking about a place.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Well, duh. It </span><span class="c1 c7">is </span><span class="c1">supposed to lead us to the flask, which is, ya know, </span><span class="c1 c7">in a place</span><span class="c1">. </span><span class="c1">That&rsquo;s if</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;this is even a real clue. I bet Arlene&rsquo;s just distracting us with this dumb puzzle while we slowly die from poison. Hey, are you even listening to me, kid?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Aidan hushes her, still staring at the riddle. Marissa glares at him, clearly taken aback, but he doesn&rsquo;t notice. Instead, he runs his finger across the first line again and mutters, &ldquo;&lsquo;House of many worlds&rsquo;... Maybe it&rsquo;s a big place with other places inside it.&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;What? Like a state?&rdquo; Marissa </span><span class="c1">suggests.</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Yeah, like that!&rdquo; He pauses, gnawing on his index finger. &ldquo;Except a state doesn&rsquo;t really feel like a &lsquo;world&rsquo;. But what else has places?&rdquo; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Dunno, a map, a universe, a, uh, I dunno, country, maybe a&mdash;&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan gasps, and Marissa lets out an exasperated sigh. &ldquo;Yeah? What is it?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;A universe!&rdquo; Aidan says. &ldquo;That might be it!&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Huh? Isn&rsquo;t that too big?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Uh-huh, but what if it&rsquo;s like the Marvel Universe? With superheroes and supervillains and stuff?&rdquo; His face is glowing with excitement. &