Then, to Aidan: &ldquo;I told you Arlene&rsquo;s traps are the best.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Aidan nods in agreement, wiping the laughing-tears away from his eyes. Inside the door, atop a spring and still bobbing back and forth like a drunkard, is a</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;jack-in-the-box</span><span class="c1">. The face is painted white with comic dots of red on each cheek and a silly tongue lolling out of its open mouth. Drawn onto its forehead between tufts of orange, plastic hair is the word &ldquo;</span><span class="c2">Gotcha!</span><span class="c1">&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s check inside,&rdquo; Marissa says once they&rsquo;ve managed to get a hold of themselves again. Aidan follows her in with a nod, and they both begin digging around the small room. On the same side as the door, a projector juts towards the big theater screen. It rests atop a thick wooden desk with a couple drawers. Aidan pulls these open but finds nothing other than some old electrical equipment and a couple broken reels of film that don&rsquo;t even seem to belong with the projector. He pops these open just in case, but there is nothing inside. Wired into the projector is a </span><span class="c1">small DVD player</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;which proves to be equally empty. Marissa searches the cabinets on the other side of the room, but comes up with the same results.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not in here,&rdquo; she groans. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s not even a single movie in this room.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Where does Arlene usually keep movies?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;How should I know? Wouldn&rsquo;t you keep them in the theater? What&rsquo;s that stupid riddle say anyway?&rdquo; She pulls the crumpled riddle out of her pocket and reads the first segment aloud. &ldquo;I am the house of many worlds, now mark my words in silence.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Now mark my words in silence,&rdquo; Aidan repeats under his breath.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;That important or something?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Uhh&hellip; well, you&rsquo;re supposed to be quiet in a theater, but still&hellip; I feel like we missed something.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;And what might that be, Detective Creepy?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;My brother and I used to like doing riddles before&mdash;&rdquo; He cuts off abruptly, glancing at Marissa for a moment before seeming satisfied that she hadn&rsquo;t noticed. Her eyes have become bleary again, and she shakes her head to refocus. &ldquo;We used to like doing riddles,&rdquo; Aidan continues, &ldquo;and he told me once that the key is to focus on the words. Every detail is important.&rdquo; He pauses for a moment. &ldquo;Words. And mark my </span><span class="c1 c7">words</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;in silence.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Great,&rdquo; Marissa says, resting her weight against the wall, one hand on her head, &ldquo;and what&rsquo;s </span><span class="c1 c7">that</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;mean?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I think,&rdquo; Aidan says, &ldquo;that means we&rsquo;re in the wrong place. Arlene said she was going to catch up on some reading, right?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Yeah, so?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;So, where does she keep her books?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;</span><span class="c1">The library. Duh</span><span class="c1">.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;That&rsquo;s it! I kinda got really caught up on the movie idea because I saw the theater before, but a library can be considered a house of many worlds too! And, it says &lsquo;mark my words in silence.&rsquo; Where do you find words?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;In a book?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Yeah! That&rsquo;s what makes it different from a theater. We&rsquo;re looking for a book in the library.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">Marissa wavers on her feet and grasps the desk with the projector on it. &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s hurry. I don&rsquo;t&hellip; feel so good.&rdquo; She leads Aidan to the library, occasionally groping for the wall to regain her balance. Once, her legs wobble and give out, and Aidan attempts to help her up.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Quit touchin&rsquo; me,&rdquo; she says weakly, shrugging him off. She claps her hands over her head, shakes herself, and manages to regain her feet. &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s go.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">They enter the library.</span></p><p class="c3 c4"><span class="c1"></span></p><h3 class="c3 c10 c5"><a name="h.cpeowdjv6hoo"></a><span class="c6">8</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Aww, again?&rdquo; Marc whines as April scoops the small pile of poker chips from the center of the table into her own stack. Marc tosses his cards towards April who slides them back into the deck and begins a well-practiced shuffle. A large pile of chips lies in front of her, neatly stacked in fives. On Marc&rsquo;s side, there are only four chips, laid out sadly as if they had fallen from April&rsquo;s stash by accident. &ldquo;Guess I&rsquo;m not too good at this game after all. I always was a bigger fan of Uno. Still,&rdquo; he says grinning, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m feeling pretty good about this next hand.&rdquo; He nudges two of his last chips into the center and leans back as April matches his bet and deals the cards.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;He picks up his cards and studies them. Eight and Two. &ldquo;Double down.&rdquo; He slides his last two chips into the pool, and April regards him with a dull expression.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Are you sure? You&rsquo;ve just gone all in.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I told you, I&rsquo;m feeling pretty good about this hand.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;You said that about the last eight,&rdquo; she says, tossing two of her chips into the center and sliding him another card. She takes another for herself.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Yeah, but I mean it this time. Ready?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They both flip up their cards.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc: &ldquo;21&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;April: &ldquo;20&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc laughs. &ldquo;Woah, that was too close! I had a ten, so I doubled down, but that was one lucky ace, huh?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Very lucky.&rdquo; April tosses two more chips into the pot. &ldquo;Nice blackjack,&rdquo; she says a little sourly.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Yeah, now you gotta watch out cuz I&rsquo;m back in the game!&rdquo; He pulls the ten chips in the center over to his side. His pile, although messy, is now the same size as April&rsquo;s. She deals another hand.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;So, April,&rdquo; Marc begins, picking up his cards and giving them a distracted glance. They don&rsquo;t seem to hold much interest now that he&rsquo;s not down to his last chips. &ldquo;If you don&rsquo;t want to answer this, I won&rsquo;t press it or anything, but why don&rsquo;t you wanna join the party?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;April looks up from her cards mildly. In a furtive voice: &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want to answer.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Alright, that&rsquo;s fine. Hit, by the way.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;She tosses him another card, looks at her own hand again, and then asks him if he&rsquo;d like to hit or stay. He stays, and they both reveal their cards.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Bust,&rdquo; Marc says and raises his palms to the air in a what-can-you-do gesture. April takes the pot and flicks four more cards out in front of them.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;How long have you been staying with Arlene?&rdquo; Marc asks.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;April just shrugs. &ldquo;A while, I guess. Time&rsquo;s strange here.&rdquo; She casts a somewhat hesitant glance at the clock in the corner, notices it still reads midnight, and shudders.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Still weirds you out? Guess you haven&rsquo;t been around for too long after all.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Guess not. What would you like to do by the way?&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Oh, uh, stay.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They both flip up their cards again, and April sweeps the pot into her own pile.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;Jeez, I think I used up all my luck on that double down,&rdquo; Marc says. &ldquo;I only seem to get lucky when I bet a lot. Ya bet big, ya win big, right?&rdquo; He pushes his eight remaining chips into the pot.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">April raises her stolid gaze to meet his eyes. &ldquo;You bet big, you fall hard.&rdquo; She grins ruefully and deals the next hand. Marc picks it up and frowns. </span><span class="c1">&ldquo;How&rsquo;s that lucky hand?&rdquo; she</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;teases, already reading on his face that the hand was anything but lucky. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Oh, it&rsquo;s great. Hit me.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">She begins to deal a card, and Marc cuts her off.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;No, I mean seriously hit me. Right here.&rdquo; He gestures at his cheek. &ldquo;For betting that much on this terrible hand.&rdquo; Marc flinches when she actually reaches across the table, punches him lightly on the shoulder, and laughs into her still curled up fist.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;You have to be careful what you bet, Marc,&rdquo; she says with a more serious tone. &ldquo;I learned that the hard way.&rdquo; Marc seems about to inquire further when she continues. &ldquo;You asked why I don&rsquo;t want to join the party. Let&rsquo;s just say that I bet on the wrong crowd once, and I don&rsquo;t intend to do it again.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c1">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Marc regards her, a little more seriously himself, for a moment. &ldquo;Sorry to hear it, but we&rsquo;re an alright crowd, if that means anything to you. In fact, I&rsquo;d say we&rsquo;ve got a pretty awesome crowd. But I won&rsquo;t push the issue.&rdquo; He looks at his cards again, clicks his tongue with distaste, and flips them for April to see. &ldquo;Doubt I can push the issue with this hand anyway. Sixteen.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">April flips hers over as well. &ldquo;Guess not. Nineteen.&rdquo; She adds the pot to her pile, not looking up. Marc stands up and stretches.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;d better get back to the party then and let Arlene know I&rsquo;ve gambled away whatever ridiculous invitation she may have been planning for you.&rdquo; He chuckles at the thought and heads for the door. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s been fun playing with you. Maybe I&rsquo;ll stop by here again if you don&rsquo;t mind the company.&rdquo; He pauses, giving her a moment to respond. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t mind,&rdquo; she says, smiling softly. &ldquo;I&rsquo;d like that.&rdquo;</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c1">&ldquo;Great! Well, in that case, I&rsquo;ll see you later tonight. Feel free to join the party if you change your mind by the way. Open offer.&rdquo; He casts her a friendly smile and leaves the room.</span></p></body></html>
